The `split` tactic is used on a goal of the form `P Ôćö Q`. It creates two subgoals: `P Ôćĺ Q` and `Q Ôćĺ P`.
The first subgoal `P Ôćĺ Q` is `rw_bisim (Exp.eval c) (Exp.eval (to_cs c)) Ôćĺ rw_bisim (Exp.eval e) (Exp.eval (to_cs c))`.
The hypothesis `h` is `rw_bisim (Exp.eval c) (Exp.eval (to_cs c))`.
So, `exact h` solves this first subgoal.

The second subgoal `Q Ôćĺ P` is `rw_bisim (Exp.eval e) (Exp.eval (to_cs c)) Ôćĺ rw_bisim (Exp.eval c) (Exp.eval (to_cs c))`.
The tactic `intro h` introduces `h : rw_bisim (Exp.eval e) (Exp.eval (to_cs c))`.
The goal becomes `rw_bisim (Exp.eval c) (Exp.eval (to_cs c))`.
The tactic `exfalso` changes the goal to `False`.
The tactic `tauto` attempts to prove `False` from the available hypotheses.
The relevant hypotheses are:
